Keep in mind that terrorism is only one possible explanation at this point. And we have no evidence yet that it has anything to do with terrorism beyond that it would fit nicely into what the conspiracy theorists want to believe is true. Another very possible and plausible explanation is that he committed suicide (and murder in the process). Or, it's possible and plausible that someone else had entered the cockpit, disabled the co-pilot, and crashed the plane. It's still too early to state affirmatively that the co-pilot is the one responsible and that it was a terrorist act.
